    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What do I need to disclose when selling a Brisbane home with solar panels?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You must disclose any known defects with the solar system, including inverter faults, panel damage, or connectivity issues. If the system is subject to a finance arrangement, lease, or power purchase agreement, buyers and their solicitors need to see the contract before they exchange. Legacy feed-in tariff rates do not transfer automatically to the new owner and you should not imply they will in your marketing. If there is a solar loan registered against the title, it must be discharged before or at settlement."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What documentation should I prepare before selling a Brisbane home with solar?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Gather the original installer's certificate, the product datasheets for the panels and inverter, all warranty documentation and confirm whether each warranty is transferable, the most recent solar generation and export data from your monitoring app or inverter display, and any maintenance or service records. If the system is on a lease or power purchase agreement, include the full contract. Having this documentation ready removes a common source of delays and buyer uncertainty during the contract period."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What do building inspectors check when inspecting a solar system in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A Brisbane building inspector will typically look at the condition of the roof around panel mounts and penetrations, the visible condition of the panels and their racking, the state of the cabling from roof to inverter, the inverter itself (age, condition, any fault codes displayed), and whether the system has a compliant isolator switch. They will note whether the system appears to be generating correctly if it is a clear day, and flag anything that looks like it needs maintenance or poses a safety concern. They do not typically test the system's output performance in detail."
      }
    }
  ]
}</script>

