      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Brisbane Home With Solar Panels: What to Disclose and How to Market It
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Solar is a genuine selling point in Brisbane's inner east, but only when it is documented, disclosed properly, and presented honestly. Here is what to prepare before you list.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Solar panels are on a large proportion of homes in Brisbane's inner east, and they are increasingly part of the buyer conversation during campaigns. When a system is well-documented and presented correctly, it is a genuine positive. When it is not, it becomes a source of uncertainty that buyers and their solicitors pick at during the contract period. The difference between those two outcomes is almost entirely preparation, not luck.</p>

      <p>This guide focuses on what to have ready before you list: the documentation package, how to talk about the system's benefits without making claims you cannot support, and what a building inspector will actually look at when they assess the system during a buyer's inspection.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Start with your documentation package</h2>
      <p>Before your property goes live, gather the following and keep a copy accessible for your agent to share with interested buyers and their solicitors.</p>

      <p>The installer's certificate of electrical compliance is the starting point. This is the document issued by the licensed electrician who installed the system and lodged the installation with Energex. It confirms the system was installed to standard and gives buyers confidence it is not a backyard job. If you cannot find it, your installer or Energex can sometimes provide a copy.</p>

      <p>Panel and inverter datasheets tell buyers the specifics of what they are getting: the brand, model, wattage, and efficiency rating for the panels, and the brand, model, and output capacity of the inverter. These are not documents buyers will scrutinise in detail, but having them confirms you know what is on your roof and removes any impression that you are vague about the system's details.</p>

      <p>Warranty documents matter most for the inverter. Panel performance warranties are typically 25 years and transfer with the property without any action required. Inverter warranties are shorter, usually 5 to 10 years, and the transfer process varies by manufacturer. Some require the new owner to notify the manufacturer within a set period of taking ownership. Check whether your inverter warranty is still active and what the transfer procedure is, and document it clearly for the buyer.</p>

      <p>Recent generation data is the most compelling evidence of the system's actual performance. Most modern inverters connect to a monitoring app. A screenshot showing 12 months of generation and export figures is far more useful to a buyer than a vague claim about how much the system saves on power bills. If you do not have monitoring data, an electrician can run a basic output check and provide a record of that.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure obligations sellers often miss</h2>
      <p>The most common disclosure gap in solar property sales is not about the panels at all. It is about the finance.</p>

      <p>If you took out a solar loan when you installed the system and it is not yet paid off, that loan may or may not be registered against the property. If it is registered, it must be disclosed in the contract and discharged before or at settlement, just like a mortgage. Buyers and their solicitors will discover it in a title search if it is not disclosed upfront. Finding it that way creates concern and erodes trust at a point in the campaign where you want confidence, not friction.</p>

      <p>Even if the solar loan is not registered against the title and is simply a personal finance product, your solicitor should advise you on how to handle it in the contract. Your obligation is to ensure the buyer receives the system free and clear of any financial encumbrance, unless you have agreed otherwise in writing.</p>

      <p>Power purchase agreements (PPAs) and leases are a separate situation. If someone else owns the panels on your roof under a PPA or lease arrangement, that is not a simple property sale. The buyer is entering into either a transfer of the agreement or a termination, both of which have cost implications. The PPA or lease contract must be available for the buyer to review before they sign, and the transfer process should be confirmed with the provider before you launch the campaign, not during the contract period.</p>

      <p>Finally, if your system was installed before around 2012 and you are receiving a legacy feed-in tariff rate under Queensland's Solar Bonus Scheme, that rate is tied to your personal electricity account and does not pass to the buyer. The new owner will receive the current standard feed-in tariff rate, which is considerably lower. This is not something to hide or avoid in your marketing. Being clear about it upfront positions you as transparent and avoids a buyer feeling misled later.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to market solar without overclaiming</h2>
      <p>The most common marketing mistake with solar is quoting a specific dollar saving without the data to support it. Statements like "saves $2,000 a year on power bills" are believable to buyers but almost impossible to verify, and they invite scrutiny. If a buyer comes back with questions and you cannot substantiate the figure, you have created doubt about your credibility across everything else in the campaign.</p>

      <p>The better approach is to describe the system objectively and let the generation data speak. Something like: "10.4 kW rooftop solar system with 6.6 kW inverter, installed 2021, generating an average of 38 kWh per day over the past 12 months." That is specific, verifiable, and more compelling to an informed buyer than a round-number savings claim.</p>

      <p>Battery storage, if present, is worth highlighting separately. A home battery allows the household to use solar-generated electricity during the evening peak, which is where most of the cost benefit sits for owner-occupiers. The brand and capacity of the battery, and whether it qualifies for any grid-support programs through the retailer, are details worth including in the marketing materials.</p>

      <p>If your system is older and you are not confident in its current output, an independent solar inspection before the campaign will give you a credible assessment to quote. The cost is typically a few hundred dollars and the report is transferable to the buyer. A clean inspection report presented proactively is more reassuring to buyers than silence followed by an inspection finding.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What building inspectors actually look at</h2>
      <p>Building and pest inspectors in Queensland are not solar technicians and do not perform a detailed performance assessment of the system. What they do check is visible condition and safety compliance, and their findings go into a written report that buyers read carefully before deciding whether to proceed.</p>

      <p>The roof penetrations around panel mounts are what a thorough inspector focuses on first. Older installations sometimes have mounts that have shifted slightly over time, creating minor gaps where water can track. This is not uncommon on Brisbane timber roofs that move with the seasons. The inspector will note any penetrations that look like they warrant further assessment or sealing, and a buyer receiving that report will ask questions.</p>

      <p>The cabling from the panels to the inverter is checked for condition and whether it is correctly secured and protected from UV degradation. Exposed, aging cable is flagged as a maintenance item. The inverter itself is inspected visually for condition, checked for any fault codes displayed on the screen, and noted for its approximate age. An inverter displaying a fault code on inspection day is a problem, even if it resets itself later.</p>

      <p>The isolator switch, typically mounted near the inverter, must meet current standards. Systems installed before 2014 may have older isolators that have since been subject to product safety notices. If your system is pre-2014, it is worth having an electrician check the isolator before your campaign and replace it if needed. The cost is low and a known isolator issue appearing in a building inspection report creates disproportionate concern in the buyer's mind.</p>

      <p>One practical step: if the system is operational and it is a clear day on inspection day, the inspector will note whether the inverter display shows it generating. Turn the system on if it has been switched off, and make sure the monitoring system is active. An inspector noting "system appeared to be generating correctly" is a neutral positive. One noting "system was switched off and could not be assessed" is not.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pulling it together before you list</h2>
      <p>The preparation checklist for a Brisbane home with solar is not long. Locate your installer certificate, panel and inverter datasheets, and warranty documents. Confirm whether the inverter warranty is still active and how it transfers. Pull 12 months of generation data from your monitoring app. If the system is on a lease, PPA, or financed product, get the contract and speak to your solicitor about the sale implications before you go to market. Have an electrician do a quick health check if the system is more than eight years old or if you are not sure about the isolator.</p>

      <p>With that in hand, your agent can present the system confidently, buyers and their solicitors will have the information they need without asking for it, and the solar component of the sale will move from a potential source of contract-stage friction to a clear positive in your campaign.</p>

